One simple way is to use [`Float.NaN`][1]:

    float x = Float.NaN;  // &lt;--

    if (x == x) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Ok&quot;);
    } else {
        System.out.println(&quot;Not ok&quot;);
    }

&lt;pre&gt;
Not ok
&lt;/pre&gt;

You can do the same with [`Double.NaN`][2].

---

From [**JLS &#167;15.21.1.** Numerical Equality Operators `==` and `!=`][3]:

&gt;Floating-point equality testing is performed in accordance with the rules of the IEEE 754 standard:
&gt;
&gt;- If either operand is NaN, then the result of `==` is `false` but the result of `!=` is `true`.  
&gt;
&gt;   Indeed, the test `x!=x` is `true` if and only if the value of `x` is NaN.
&gt;
&gt;...

  [1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Float.html#NaN
  [2]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Double.html#NaN
  [3]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.21.1

