## Using derived tables

As I [answered to your follow-up question][1], I don&#39;t think you really need the derived table. You&#39;ll simplify your life greatly, if you just remove it.

## Dereferencing columns from a derived table

If your actual query is more complex than the one you&#39;ve presented here, you&#39;ll have to dereference columns from your derived table like this:

```java
// Dereference first:
Field&lt;String&gt; status = orgWiseCountTable.field(&quot;status&quot;, String.class);

// Alternatively, dereference using generaetd code for added convenience:
Field&lt;String&gt; status = orgWiseCountTable.field(THE_TABLE.STATUS);

// Then use in expressions:
DSL.count().filterWhere(status.eq(&quot;Completed&quot;)).as(&quot;SuccessCount&quot;);
```

## Aggregate filter clause

Note, I&#39;m using [`FILTER`][2] instead, which is a standard SQL feature. This will be a bit more convenient to write in jOOQ, than using the MySQL specific approach of mapping booleans to integers in order to sum them. `A.eq(B)` is a `Condition` in jOOQ, which extends `Field&lt;Boolean&gt;`, and you cannot really sum booleans.

## Code generation

This isn&#39;t necessary relevant to your question, but I highly recommend you [start using jOOQ&#39;s code generator][3]. A lot of features will be unlocked by that, and your queries will be much simpler to write.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/75554469/521799
  [2]: https://www.jooq.org/doc/latest/manual/sql-building/column-expressions/aggregate-functions/aggregate-filter/
  [3]: https://blog.jooq.org/why-you-should-use-jooq-with-code-generation/

