ECMAScript, as well as all other flavors supported by the `std::regex`, does not support Unicode properties (Unicode category classes). 

As a workaround, use [Boost library][1] in C++.

In Boost, declare the regex as follows:

    boost::wregex reg(L&quot;^\\p{L}+$&quot;);

Note that `^\p{L}+$` matches 1+ letter strings only.

In ECMAScript used in JavaScript in modern browsers, you can use

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var str = &quot;bębnić&quot;;
    var regex = /^\p{L}+$/u;
    console.log(regex.test(str));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

An [XRegExp based solution][2] in JavaScript for older browsers (like Safari):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var str = &quot;bębnić&quot;;
    regex = XRegExp(&#39;^\\p{L}+$&#39;);
    console.log(regex.test(str));

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/xregexp/2.0.0/xregexp-all-min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

  [1]: http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_59_0_b1/libs/regex/doc/html/boost_regex/ref/non_std_strings/icu.html
  [2]: http://xregexp.com/

